":"1416","Scotland":"Scotland","Stornoway Castle, Lewis, Scotland":"Stornoway, Ross-shire, Scotland","Ross-shire, Scotland":"Ross-shire, Scotland","Lochbroom, Ross-shire, Scotland":"Lochbroom, Ross-shire, Scotland","Kintail, Ross-shire, Scotland":"Kintail, Ross-shire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacLeod","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McLeod  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McLeod","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Leòid</b> ‘son of <i>Leòd</i>’, a patronymic from a Gaelic form of Old Norse <i>Liótr</i> ‘ugly’, a common personal name in medieval Norway and Iceland.","History: This is the name of a major Scottish Hebridean clan, associated in particular with Dunvegan on the isle of Skye; also, historically, with the island of Lewis. There are two main branches: the McLeods of Harris and Dunvegan (Sìol Tormoid) and the McLeods of Lewis (Sìol Torcaill). Both branches claim descent from a certain Leòd (Norse: <i>Liótr</i>), who lived in the 13th century. — One prominent bearer of this prominent Scottish name, Alexander McLeod (1774–1833), a Reformed Presbyterian clergyman, author, and editor, emigrated to the US in 1792 from the island of Mull in the Hebrides."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Finguala MacLeod of Harris was born in 1374, in Ross-shire, Scotland, her father, Malcolm MacLeod 3rd Clan Chief, was 78 and her mother, Lady Martha Domhnall - Lady of Mar, was 49. She married Murdoch Mackenzie 5th Laird of Kintail about 1395, in Kintail, Ross-shire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1416, in Scotland, at the age of 42, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1374–1416":"1374–1416","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1363–1416":"1363–1416","1398–1488":"1398–1488","1296–1380":"1296–1380","1325–1402":"1325–1402","before 1368":"enne 1368","5 September 1402":"5. september 1402","1374":"1374","1363":"1363","1296":"1296","1370":"1370","1380":"1380",